ally if a response isn't fully received even with the proper content-length. Maybe I should write the response first, then pause before closing to ensure everything is sent correctly. I could explore using a CountDownLatch for synchronizing responses. Jetty seems to understand content length, so that gives me some confidence. However, I need to handle timeouts carefully to avoid issues if a response fails to come through.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering server response handling**\\n\\nI'm exploring how to manage server responses with timeout settings effectively. One idea is to accept and set a socket timeout, then write a response and flush it. It might be okay to catch EOFException during this process, but what if there's no request? In that case, a socket timeout could throw an IOException. I wonder if I should avoid reading altogether and instead just write the response first and pause briefly, allowing the client to proceed.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_hswwu81enYKd3LRIL89GcIX3|fc_0e0983f2998288b6016a26d959d7f88194931892b9004fcbd6", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.springframework/spring-web/5.3.32/src/test/java/org_springframework/spring_web/JettyClientHttpResponseTest.java", "edits": [{"oldText": "import java.io.EOFException;\nimport java.io.IOException;\nimport java.io.InputStream;\nimport java.io.OutputStream;", "newText": "import java.io.IOException;\nimport java.io.OutputStream;"}, {"oldText": "        try (Socket socket = serverSocket.accept()) {\n            socket.setSoTimeout(10_000);\n            readHttpRequest(socket.getInputStream());\n            byte[] body = \"hello jetty\".getBytes(StandardCharsets.UTF_8);", "newText": "        try (Socket socket = serverSocket.accept()) {\n            byte[] body = \"hello jetty\".getBytes(StandardCharsets.UTF_8);"}, {"oldText": "            output.write(body);\n            output.flush();\n            return null;\n        } catch (IOException ex) {\n   